In Kyiv, Oleksandr Glyadelov's images defy the bombs
description: The Donbas, the Maidan Revolution, Bucha… For 35 years, Ukrainian photographer Oleksandr Glyadelov has documented the history of his country. Starting September 5, the Ukrainian House in Kyiv will present a major retrospective of his work. The exhibition pays tribute to the spirit of national resistance.

headline: Venus Williams wins a US Open women's doubles match for the first time since 2014 – and without Serena
description: Tennis star Venus Williams, 45, was playing doubles at a major for the first time since the 2022 US Open, her sister Serena Williams' final tournament. On Thursday, Venus partnered with Leylah Fernandez to defeat the sixth-seeded pair of Lyudmyla Kichenok and Ellen Perez 7-6 (4), 6-3.

headline: How Argentina fell in love with a poetic live stream from the depths of the ocean: 'Patrick the Starfish is Argentinian!'
description: By filming the depths of the South Atlantic this summer, a scientific mission sparked unprecedented enthusiasm. The project brought much-needed attention to public research, which has been left struggling after budget cuts by President Milei.

headline: PSG's Ousmane Dembélé: 'The Ballon d'Or is the Holy Grail'
description: The Paris Saint-Germain forward is considered a top contender for the prestigious award recognizing the best football player of the season. Speaking to Le Monde, the Frenchman emphasized his club's collective performance over his individual achievements.

description: 'The Enigma of Mohammed VI' (5/6). In order to maintain his power, the Moroccan monarch relies on a handful of loyal supporters, most of whom he has known for decades. However, internal rivalries betray a certain nervousness, revealing the uncertainty surrounding the future of his reign.

headline: At the Venice Film Festival, French filmmakers take on literary adaptation
description: Valérie Donzelli, François Ozon, Cédric Jimenez and Olivier Assayas are all presenting films adapted from novels at the Mostra, running from August 27 to September 6.

headline: Jacques Rancière, philosopher: 'Today, the people fueled by resentment manufactured by billionaires dominate the public sphere'
description: 'May '68 Thinkers Reflect On Trump Era' (1/6). The philosopher of emancipation examines the roots of the current reactionary offensive. He views contemporary utopian micro-communities as new ways of 'living as equals.'
